Date:10/25/2008 12:57:35 PM
From:Jurgis Bekepuris
Spek, do you use Morningstar reports for your DD? :) Your thoughts sound a lot
like their reports. :)

CSCO - I went to a talk by their CEO couple weeks ago. Of course, he claims
that CSCO will gain market share and grow during the slowdown.

However, CSCOs big push now is teleconferencing and collaborative work.
Teleconferencing is definitely getting more use with business travel budgets
cut. It is just not clear that CSCO will get great revenues and margins from
teleconferencing. Companies try to get cheapest solutions although there is
some barrier of entry for high end videoconferencing. Even there I am not sure
CSCO is the leader.

Collaborative work is even more questionable. IMHO this is strictly software
domain where CSCO is not an expert in any way. MSFT is probably the company
best positioned to benefit from any collaborative work improvements, since they
control the OS and they can use that knowledge and expertise to enable
document/work sharing. Even then I have not seen a lot of successful examples
of collaborative work. Most people still just send around documents as files
and collaborate through email, phone, IM. Screen sharing solutions are used
sometimes, but that's mostly MSFT and IBM and perhaps Interwise by AT&T. So
color me a sceptic on any breakthroughs in collaborative work and that CSCO
will be a leader there. BTW, I regularly attend research presentations in this
area and again IBM + MSFT are clear leaders. And IMHO even their research is
mostly not convincing.

Anyway, I still think that CSCO will do well, but not necessarily spectacularly
well. :) I own a small position.

I have not looked at INTC in depth recently. I did not like their situation of
pretty much competing with AMD on price. Their ROE is not that great and they
are not very cheap here.

MSFT - I love its cash cow aspect. I am not sure if they will be able to
transform the company into something like IBM: with more focus on services for
long term. They are doing some good things. I own a small position.

I think that GOOG is coming to buy range. It could be a good buy in terms of
moat, valuation is the key question though. There is also a risk that their
income is concentrated in a single area, while their attempts to diversify so
far have been more of attempts to diworsesify. There is no clarity that the new
products bring a lot of revenue, earnings or leadership. They may strike gold
somewhere though.

ORCL and ADBE may be another couple to follow. Not cheap though.
