%BOM---------------------
Date:10/30/2008 10:44:56 PM
From:Paul Senior
EKS, my tactic is to sell higher cost shares that are now losses. Generally
those higher-cost shares are recent buys (less than 1 year). I've got enough
losers where with some, to keep the position size, I can sell now and buy back
in 31 days, and some where I figure stock is so low I'm better buying more now
and maybe selling some 31 days later. Just a guess which way to go.

Right now I have net long-term capital gains which exceed my net short-term
capital losses.

My intent is to continue selling short-term losers to the point where net
short-term losses exceed net long-term gains by a goodly amount. Selling to the
extent this will give me a $3000 off-set to income and where I'm sure I'll have
a substantially net short-term loss carryover into 2009 (to use against any
capital gains I might have in 2009).

Last year I had huge amounts of capital gains (compared to my previous taxable
income) that I had to pay taxes & AMT stuff on. This year, because I've so many
stocks in a losing position, I'll minimize my overall tax bill while trying to
position myself for some capital gains maybe in 2010/2011 -- if capital gains
would even be possible in the market then.
