From:Spekulatius
HIG - was briefly discussed here a few month ago. i think i pointed out a CS
report indicating problematic assets on balance sheet. Now all major life
insurers have problems on their balance sheet. I think MET's book value
including unrealized losses went down 10$/share YOY. Life insurers have LT
contracts so they do not have to show unrealized losses on investments unless
considered impaired, but still this is a scary number. I would guess that MET
should be OK and in case there is a run on life insurers the treasury would put
them under their TARP. PRU should be similar.

I don't own any of those, though. I do have a position in HMO UNH and recently
WLP. I consider adding to AET as well. Those HMO have fairly little balance
sheet risk but it's a low margin business where small errors can have a
significant impact on operating margins as we have seen the last year <ng>.
Potentially we have some political risk as well - still I take that over the
imponderables for the life insurers at this point.
